org/wiki/Special:EditPage/Template:US_Constitution_article_series" title=3D=
"Special:EditPage/Template:US Constitution article series"><abbr title=3D"E=
dit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The <b>Equal Rights Amendment</b> (<b>ERA</b>) is a proposed amendment t=
o the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_United_S=
tates" title=3D"Constitution of the United States">United States Constituti=
on</a> that would explicitly prohibit sex discrimination. It is not current=
ly a part of the Constitution, though its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ratification#Ratification_in_the_United_States_Constitution" title=
=3D"Ratification">ratification</a> status has long been debated. It was wri=
tten by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Paul" title=3D"Alice=
 Paul">Alice Paul</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_=
Eastman" title=3D"Crystal Eastman">Crystal Eastman</a> and first introduced=
 in Congress in December 1923. With the rise of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Second-wave_feminism_in_the_United_States" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Second-wave feminism in the United States">women's movemen=
t in the United States</a> during the 1960s, the ERA garnered increasing su=
pport, and, after being reintroduced by Representative <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_Griffiths" title=3D"Martha Griffiths">Martha Gr=
iffiths</a> in 1971, it was approved by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/United_States_House_of_Representatives" title=3D"United States Ho=
use of Representatives">U.S. House of Representatives</a> that year, and by=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Senate" title=
=3D"United States Senate">U.S. Senate</a> in 1972, thus submitting the ERA =
to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/State_legislature_(United_S=
tates)" title=3D"State legislature (United States)">state legislatures</a> =
for ratification, as provided by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
rticle_Five_of_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Article Five of the=
 United States Constitution">Article Five of the United States Constitution=
</a>. A seven-year, 1979, deadline was included with the legislation by Con=
gress. A simple majority of Congress later extended the deadline to 1982. B=
oth deadlines passed with the ERA three short of the necessary 38&nbsp;stat=
es for ratification. Even so, there are ongoing efforts to ratify the amend=
ment.
</p><p>The purpose of the ERA is to guarantee equal legal rights for all Am=
erican citizens regardless of sex. In the early history of the Equal Rights=
 Amendment, middle-class women were largely supportive, while those speakin=
g for the working class were often opposed, arguing that women should hold =
more domestic responsibility than men and that employed women needed specia=
l protections regarding working conditions and employment hours. Proponents=
 asserted it would end legal distinctions between men and women in matters =
including divorce, property, and employment. Opponents have argued that it =
would remove protections from women and open women to be drafted into the m=
ilitary.
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Resolution_text">Resolution=
 text</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_=
Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: =
Resolution text"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>The resolution, "Proposing an amendment to the Constitution of the Unite=
d States relative to equal rights for men and women", reads, in part:<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p><i>Resolved by the Senate and House =
of Representatives of the United States of America in Congress assembled</i=
> (<i>two-thirds of each House concurring therein</i>), That the following =
article is proposed as an amendment to the Constitution of the United State=
s, which shall be valid to all intents and purposes as part of the Constitu=
tion when ratified by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several Stat=
es within seven years from the date of its submission by the Congress:
</p><p>"<b>ARTICLE</b> =E2=80=94
</p><p>"<b>Section 1.</b> Equality of rights under the law shall not be den=
ied or abridged by the United States or by any State on account of sex.
</p><p>"<b>Section 2.</b> The Congress shall have the power to enforce, by =
appropriate legislation, the provisions of this article.
</p><p>
"<b>Section 3.</b> This amendment shall take effect two years after the dat=
e of ratification."</p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Early_history_(1920s=E2=80=
=931940s)"><span id=3D"Early_history_.281920s.E2.80.931940s.29"></span>Earl=
y history (1920s=E2=80=931940s)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
3" title=3D"Edit section: Early history (1920s=E2=80=931940s)"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Alice_paul.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Alic=
e_paul.jpg/250px-Alice_paul.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"353" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"828" data-file-height=3D=
"1170"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Paul"=
 title=3D"Alice Paul">Alice Paul</a> toasting (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Prohibition_in_the_United_States" title=3D"Prohibition in the =
United States">with grape juice</a>) the passage of the Nineteenth Amendmen=
t, August 26, 1920<sup id=3D"cite_ref-WhoWas_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-WhoWas=
-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>On September 25, 1921, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nati=
onal_Woman%27s_Party" title=3D"National Woman's Party">National Woman's Par=
ty</a> announced its plans to campaign for an amendment to the U.S. Constit=
ution to guarantee women equal rights with men. The text of the proposed am=
endment read:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote">
<p>Section 1. No political, civil, or legal disabilities or inequalities on=
 account of sex or on account of marriage, unless applying equally to both =
sexes, shall exist within the United States or any territory subject to the=
 jurisdiction thereof.
</p><p>
Section 2. Congress shall have power to enforce this article by appropriate=
 legislation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BaltSun_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-BaltSun-=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Alice Paul, the head of the National Women's Party, believed that the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nineteenth_Amendment_to_the_United_S=
tates_Constitution" title=3D"Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Cons=
titution">Nineteenth Amendment</a> would not be enough to ensure that men a=
nd women were treated equally regardless of sex. In 1923, at <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seneca_Falls,_New_York" title=3D"Seneca Falls, N=
ew York">Seneca Falls, New York</a>, she revised the proposed amendment to =
read:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Men and women shall have=
 equal rights throughout the United States and every place subject to its j=
urisdiction. Congress shall have power to enforce this article by appropria=
te legislation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-WhoWas_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-WhoWas-2=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Paul named this version the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luc=
retia_Mott" title=3D"Lucretia Mott">Lucretia Mott</a> Amendment, after a fe=
male abolitionist who fought for women's rights and attended the First Wome=
n's Rights Convention.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-4"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The proposal was seconded by Dr. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Frances_Dickinson_(physician)" title=3D"Frances Dickinson (physician)">Fr=
ances Dickinson</a>, a cousin of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
usan_B._Anthony" title=3D"Susan B. Anthony">Susan B. Anthony</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-LATimes-22jul1923_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-LATimes-22jul1923-5"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>Following its introduction in 1923, the Equal Rights Amendment was r=
eintroduced in each subsequent Congress, but made little progress.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amend=
ment#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-8"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>In 1943, Alice Paul further revised the amendment to reflect the wor=
ding of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifteenth_Amendment_to=
_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Fifteenth Amendment to the United=
 States Constitution">Fifteenth</a> and Nineteenth Amendments. This text wo=
uld later become Section 1 of the version passed by Congress in 1972.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-auto_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-auto-9"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As a result of this revision, ERA opponents proposed an alternative =
in the 1940s. This alternative provided that "no distinctions on the basis =
of sex shall be made except such as are reasonably justified by differences=
 in physical structure, biological differences, or social function." It was=
 quickly rejected by both pro- and anti-ERA coalitions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Righ=
ts_Amendment#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourteenth_Amendme=
nt_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Fourteenth Amendment to the =
United States Constitution">Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Const=
itution</a> was adopted in 1868, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Equal_Protection_Clause" title=3D"Equal Protection Clause">Equal Protect=
ion Clause</a>, which guarantees equal protection of the laws, did not appl=
y to women. It was not until 1972 that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Supreme Court of the =
United States">United States Supreme Court</a> extended equal protection to=
 sex-based discrimination.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-11"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> However, women have never been entitled to full equal protection =
as the Court subsequently ruled that statutory or administrative sex classi=
fications were subject to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter=
mediate_scrutiny" title=3D"Intermediate scrutiny">intermediate standard of =
judicial review</a>, a less stringent standard than that applied to other f=
orms of discrimination.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-12"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Split_among_feminists">Spli=
t among feminists</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Split among feminists"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since the 1920s, the Equal Rights Amendment has been accompanied by disc=
ussion among <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feminism" title=3D"Fe=
minism">feminists</a> about the meaning of women's equality.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal=
_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Alice_Paul" title=3D"Alice Paul">Alice Paul</a> and her <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Woman%27s_Party" title=3D"Nation=
al Woman's Party">National Woman's Party</a> asserted that women should be =
on equal terms with men in all regards, even if that means sacrificing bene=
fits given to women through protective legislation, such as shorter work ho=
urs and no night work or heavy lifting.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cit=
e_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Opponents of the amendment, such as the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Joint_Congressional_Committee" title=
=3D"Women's Joint Congressional Committee">Women's Joint Congressional Comm=
ittee</a>, believed that the loss of these benefits to women would not be w=
orth the supposed gain to them in equality. In 1924, <i>The Forum</i> hoste=
d a debate between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doris_Stevens" =
title=3D"Doris Stevens">Doris Stevens</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Alice_Hamilton" title=3D"Alice Hamilton">Alice Hamilton</a> con=
cerning the two perspectives on the proposed amendment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Righ=
ts_Amendment#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Their debate reflected the wider ten=
sion in the developing feminist movement of the early 20th century between =
two approaches toward gender equality. One approach emphasized the common h=
umanity of women and men, while the other stressed women's unique experienc=
es and how they were different from men, seeking recognition for specific n=
eeds.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The opposit=
ion to the ERA was led by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_And=
erson_(labor_leader)" title=3D"Mary Anderson (labor leader)">Mary Anderson<=
/a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Bureau" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Women's Bureau">Women's Bureau</a> beginning in =
1923. These feminists argued that legislation including mandated minimum wa=
ges, safety regulations, restricted daily and weekly hours, lunch breaks, a=
nd maternity provisions would be more beneficial to the majority of women w=
ho were forced to work out of economic necessity, not personal fulfillment.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The debate also =
drew from struggles between working class and professional women.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Alice Hamilton, in her spe=
ech "Protection for Women Workers", said that the ERA would strip working w=
omen of the small protections they had achieved, leaving them powerless to =
further improve their condition in the future, or to attain necessary prote=
ctions in the present.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-19"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Woman%27s_Part=
y" title=3D"National Woman's Party">National Woman's Party</a> already had =
tested its approach in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wisconsin" =
title=3D"Wisconsin">Wisconsin</a>, where it won passage of the Wisconsin Eq=
ual Rights Law in 1921.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-20"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The party=
 then took the ERA to Congress, where U.S. senator <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Curtis" title=3D"Charles Curtis">Charles Curtis</a=
>, a future <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_vice_president=
s_of_the_United_States" title=3D"List of vice presidents of the United Stat=
es">vice president of the United States</a>, introduced it for the first ti=
me in October 1921.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BaltSun_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Balt=
Sun-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Although the ERA was introduced in every congressional se=
ssion between 1921 and 1972, it almost never reached the floor of either th=
e Senate or the House for a vote. Instead, it was usually blocked in commit=
tee; except in 1946, when it was defeated in the Senate by a vote of 38 to =
35=E2=80=94not receiving the required two-thirds supermajority.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eq=
ual_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Post-World_War_II_developme=
nts_(1940s=E2=80=931960s)"><span id=3D"Post-World_War_II_developments_.2819=
40s.E2.80.931960s.29"></span>Post-World War II developments (1940s=E2=80=93=
1960s)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual=
_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Post-World War II developments (1940s=E2=80=931960s)"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D"World Wa=
r II">World War II</a> was correlated with a rise supporters of the ERA. Du=
e to the war, many women had to take on untraditional roles at home and in =
the workforce. Protectionists were against the ERA because they believed wo=
men need to be treated differently than men, because they are biologically =
different. Women entered the workforce and proved they could handle working=
 the same jobs as men, including joining the U.S. Armed Forces. Women were =
supporting their country, despite not being compensated or respected fairly=
. With the increased patriotism in the country people began to see the valu=
e of women being involved in their country. As the war continued, more oppo=
rtunities for women to work opened up due to fewer men being available. The=
 support for equality grew with this as women continued to prove their abil=
ity and willingness to work.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-23">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Initial_support_from_the_Re=
publican_Party_and_the_Hayden_rider">Initial support from the Republican Pa=
rty and the Hayden rider</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index=
.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Initial support from the Republican Party and the Hayden=
 rider"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_St=
ates)" title=3D"Republican Party (United States)">Republican Party</a> incl=
uded support of the ERA in its platform beginning in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/1940_Republican_National_Convention" title=3D"1940 Repub=
lican National Convention">1940</a>, renewing the plank every four years un=
til <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1980_United_States_presidentia=
l_election" title=3D"1980 United States presidential election">1980</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-'70s_245_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The main support base for the ERA until the late 1960s was among middle cl=
ass Republican women, while some Southern Democrats also supported it.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-:2_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-:2-25"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-'70s_245_24-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1950 and 1953, the ERA was passed by the Senate with a provision =
known as "the Hayden rider", introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Arizona" title=3D"Arizona">Arizona</a> senator <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Hayden" title=3D"Carl Hayden">Carl Hayden</a>. T=
he Hayden rider added a sentence to the ERA to keep special protections for=
 women: "The provisions of this article shall not be construed to impair an=
y rights, benefits, or exemptions now or hereafter conferred by law upon pe=
rsons of the female sex." By allowing women to keep their existing and futu=
re special protections, it was expected that the ERA would be more appealin=
g to its opponents. Though opponents were marginally more in favor of the E=
RA with the Hayden rider, supporters of the original ERA believed it negate=
d the amendment's original purpose=E2=80=94causing the amendment not to be =
passed in the House.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-26"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-auto1_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-auto1-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>ERA supporters were hopeful that the second term of President <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" title=3D"Dwight D.=
 Eisenhower">Dwight Eisenhower</a> would advance their agenda. Eisenhower h=
ad publicly promised to "assure women everywhere in our land equality of ri=
ghts," and in 1958, Eisenhower asked a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Joint_session_of_the_United_States_Congress" title=3D"Joint session of=
 the United States Congress">joint session of Congress</a> to pass the Equa=
l Rights Amendment, the first president to show such a level of support for=
 the amendment. However, the National Woman's Party found the amendment to =
be unacceptable and asked it to be withdrawn whenever the Hayden rider was =
added to the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-auto1_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-auto1-2=
8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Initial_opposition_from_the=
_New_Deal_Democrats">Initial opposition from the New Deal Democrats</h4><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendm=
ent&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Initial oppos=
ition from the New Deal Democrats"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eleanor_Roosevelt" title=3D"Ele=
anor Roosevelt">Eleanor Roosevelt</a> and most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/New_Deal" title=3D"New Deal">New Dealers</a> opposed the ERA. =
They felt that ERA was designed for middle-class women, but that working-cl=
ass women needed government protection. They also feared that the ERA would=
 undercut the male-dominated labor unions that were a core component of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Deal_coalition" title=3D"New =
Deal coalition">New Deal coalition</a>. Most Northern <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)" title=3D"Democratic P=
arty (United States)">Democrats</a>, who aligned themselves with the anti-E=
RA labor unions, opposed the amendment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-'70s_245_24-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Am=
endment#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The ERA was also opposed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/American_Federation_of_Labor" title=3D"American Federation of Labor">A=
merican Federation of Labor</a> and other labor unions, which feared the am=
endment would invalidate protective labor legislation for women. The <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_of_Women_Voters" title=3D"League =
of Women Voters">League of Women Voters</a>, formerly the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_American_Woman_Suffrage_Association" title=
=3D"National American Woman Suffrage Association">National American Woman S=
uffrage Association</a>, opposed the Equal Rights Amendment until 1972, fea=
ring the loss of protective labor legislation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_25-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_A=
mendment#cite_note-:2-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>At the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1944_Democratic_Nati=
onal_Convention" title=3D"1944 Democratic National Convention">1944 Democra=
tic National Convention</a>, the Democrats made the divisive step of includ=
ing the ERA in their platform, but this was a hotly contested change not re=
flected in later party platforms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-'70s_245_24-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> At the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/1960_Democratic_National_Convention" title=3D"1960 Democratic N=
ational Convention">Democratic National Convention in 1960</a>, a proposal =
to endorse the ERA was rejected after it was opposed by groups including th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Civil_Liberties_Union" =
title=3D"American Civil Liberties Union">American Civil Liberties Union</a>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (ACLU), the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFL-CIO" title=3D"AFL-CIO">AFL-CIO</a>=
, labor unions such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/America=
n_Federation_of_Teachers" title=3D"American Federation of Teachers">America=
n Federation of Teachers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amer=
icans_for_Democratic_Action" title=3D"Americans for Democratic Action">Amer=
icans for Democratic Action</a> (ADA), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/American_Nurses_Association" title=3D"American Nurses Association"=
>American Nurses Association</a>, the Women's Division of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methodist_Church_(USA)" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Methodist Church (USA)">Methodist Church</a>, and the National Coun=
cils of Jewish, Catholic, and Negro Women.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#=
cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Between 1948 and 1970, chairman <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Emanuel_Celler" title=3D"Emanuel Celler">Emanuel Celler</a> of the Hou=
se Judiciary Committee refused to consider the ERA in the House of Represen=
tatives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Support_from_the_Democratic=
_Party_under_Kennedy">Support from the Democratic Party under Kennedy</h4><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amen=
dment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Support fro=
m the Democratic Party under Kennedy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Presidential candidate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_F._=
Kennedy" title=3D"John F. Kennedy">John F. Kennedy</a> announced his suppor=
t of the ERA in an October 21, 1960, letter to the chairman of the National=
 Woman's Party.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-32"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Ultimately however, as president, Kennedy's ties to labor unions meant tha=
t he and his administration did not support the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_=
Amendment#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Kennedy did appoint a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue-=
ribbon_committee" title=3D"Blue-ribbon committee">blue-ribbon commission</a=
> on women, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidential_Commi=
ssion_on_the_Status_of_Women" title=3D"Presidential Commission on the Statu=
s of Women">President's Commission on the Status of Women</a>, to investiga=
te the problem of sex discrimination in the United States.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_R=
ights_Amendment#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The commission was chaired by <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eleanor_Roosevelt" title=3D"Eleanor R=
oosevelt">Eleanor Roosevelt</a>, who opposed the ERA but no longer spoke ag=
ainst it publicly. In the early 1960s, Eleanor Roosevelt announced that, du=
e to unionization, she believed the ERA was no longer a threat to women as =
it once may have been and told supporters that, as far as she was concerned=
, they could have the amendment if they wanted it. However, she never went =
so far as to endorse the ERA. The commission that she chaired reported (aft=
er her death) that no ERA was needed, believing that the Supreme Court coul=
d give sex the same "suspect" test as race and national origin, through int=
erpretation of the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments of the Constitution.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3=
6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Right=
s_Amendment#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Supreme Court did not provide the=
 "suspect" class test for sex, however, resulting in a continuing lack of e=
qual rights. The commission did, though, help win passage of the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Pay_Act_of_1963" title=3D"Equal Pay Ac=
t of 1963">Equal Pay Act of 1963</a>, which banned sex discrimination in wa=
ges in a number of professions (it would later be amended in the early 1970=
s to include the professions that it initially excluded) and secured an <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executive_order" title=3D"Executive o=
rder">executive order</a> from Kennedy eliminating sex discrimination in th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_service" title=3D"Civil se=
rvice">civil service</a>. The commission, composed largely of anti-ERA femi=
nists with ties to labor, proposed remedies to the widespread sex discrimin=
ation it unearthed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-37"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>The national commission spurred the establishment of state and local=
 commissions on the status of women and arranged for follow-up conferences =
in the years to come. The following year, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964" title=3D"Civil Rights Act of 1964">Ci=
vil Rights Act of 1964</a> banned workplace discrimination not only on the =
basis of race, religion, and national origin, but also on the basis of sex,=
 thanks to the lobbying of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_P=
aul" title=3D"Alice Paul">Alice Paul</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Coretta_Scott_King" title=3D"Coretta Scott King">Coretta Scott K=
ing</a> and the political influence of Representative <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_Griffiths" title=3D"Martha Griffiths">Martha Gri=
ffiths</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michigan" title=3D"M=
ichigan">Michigan</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-38"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Impact_of_second-wave_femin=
ism">Impact of second-wave feminism</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Impact of second-wave feminism"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shirley_Chisholm.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1=
0/Shirley_Chisholm.jpg/250px-Shirley_Chisholm.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"373" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3014" =
data-file-height=3D"4492"></a><figcaption>Shirley Chisholm, photographed in=
 1972</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second-wave_feminism" title=3D"=
Second-wave feminism">A new women's movement</a> gained ground in the later=
 1960s as a result of a variety of factors: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Betty_Friedan" title=3D"Betty Friedan">Betty Friedan</a>'s bestse=
ller <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Feminine_Mystique" tit=
le=3D"The Feminine Mystique">The Feminine Mystique</a></i>; the network of =
women's rights commissions formed by Kennedy's national commission; the fru=
stration over women's social and economic status; and anger over the lack o=
f government and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Employment_=
Opportunity_Commission" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Equal Employment Opp=
ortunity Commission">Equal Employment Opportunity Commission</a> enforcemen=
t of the Equal Pay Act and Title VII of the Civil Rights Act. In June 1966,=
 at the Third National Conference on the Status of Women in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington,_D.C." title=3D"Washington, D.C.">Wash=
ington, D.C.</a>, Betty Friedan and a group of activists frustrated with th=
e lack of government action in enforcing Title VII of the Civil Rights Act =
formed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Organization_f=
or_Women" title=3D"National Organization for Women">National Organization f=
or Women</a> (NOW) to act as an "NAACP for women", demanding full equality =
for American women and men.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schneir_1994_95_39-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-Schneir_1994_95-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1967, at the urging of Ali=
ce Paul, NOW endorsed the Equal Rights Amendment.<sup class=3D"noprint Inli=
ne-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Ci=
tation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sourc=
es. (May 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights=
_Amendment#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The decision caused some union Democra=
ts and social conservatives to leave the organization and form the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Equity_Action_League" title=3D"=
Women's Equity Action League">Women's Equity Action League</a> (within a fe=
w years WEAL also endorsed the ERA), but the move to support the amendment =
benefited NOW, bolstering its membership.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templ=
ate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation n=
eeded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May=
 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> By the late 1960s, NOW had ma=
de significant political and legislative victories and was gaining enough p=
ower to become a major lobbying force. In 1969, newly elected representativ=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shirley_Chisholm" title=3D"Shirl=
ey Chisholm">Shirley Chisholm</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/New_York_(state)" title=3D"New York (state)">New York</a> gave her famou=
s speech "Equal Rights for Women" on the floor of the U.S. House of Represe=
ntatives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Views">Views</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Views"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_support">In support</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Ame=
ndment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: In suppor=
t"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div><p>
Supporters of the ERA point to the lack of a specific guarantee in the Cons=
titution for equal rights protections on the basis of sex.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_R=
ights_Amendment#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1973, future Supreme Court jus=
tice <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_Bader_Ginsburg" title=3D=
"Ruth Bader Ginsburg">Ruth Bader Ginsburg</a> summarized a supporting argum=
ent for the ERA in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American=
_Bar_Association_Journal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"American Bar Assoc=
iation Journal">American Bar Association Journal</a></i>:</p><blockquote><p=
>The equal rights amendment, in sum, would dedicate the nation to a new vie=
w of the rights and responsibilities of men and women. It firmly rejects sh=
arp legislative lines between the sexes as constitutionally tolerable. Inst=
ead, it looks toward a legal system in which each person will be judged on =
the basis of individual merit and not on the basis of an unalterable trait =
of birth that bears no necessary relationship to need or ability.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Ginsburg_1973_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Ginsburg_1973-43"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up></p></blockquote>
<p>Later, Ginsburg voiced her opinion that the best course of action on the=
 Equal Rights Amendment is to start over, due to being past its expiration =
date.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While at a =
discussion at Georgetown University in February 2020, Ginsburg noted the ch=
allenge that "if you count a latecomer on the plus side, how can you disreg=
ard states that said 'we've changed our minds?'"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amen=
dment#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-4=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>In the early 1940s, both the Democratic and Republican parties added=
 support for the ERA to their platforms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#ci=
te_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Pro-ERA_March_during_1980_Republican_National_Convention_(Detroit,_Mich=
igan).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimed=
ia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Pro-ERA_March_during_1980_Republican_Na=
tional_Convention_%28Detroit%2C_Michigan%29.jpg/330px-Pro-ERA_March_during_=
1980_Republican_National_Convention_%28Detroit%2C_Michigan%29.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"275" height=3D"183" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"1692" data-file-height=3D"1124"></a><figcaption>Pro-ERA march at =
the 1980 Republican National Convention, the first presidential election ye=
ar that the party dropped its support for the ERA in four decades<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Organization_for_W=
omen" title=3D"National Organization for Women">National Organization for W=
omen</a> (NOW) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ERAmerica" titl=
e=3D"ERAmerica">ERAmerica</a>, a coalition of almost 80 organizations, led =
the pro-ERA efforts. Between 1972 and 1982, ERA supporters held rallies, pe=
titioned, picketed, went on hunger strikes, and performed acts of civil dis=
obedience.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ERA:_History_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-ERA:_Hi=
story-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> On July 9, 1978, NOW and other organizations hosted a=
 national march in Washington, D.C., which garnered over 100,000 supporters=
, and was followed by a Lobby Day on July 10.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On June 6, 1982, NOW sponsored marches in sta=
tes that had not passed the ERA including Florida, Illinois, North Carolina=
, and Oklahoma.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-51"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Key feminists of the time, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gloria_Steinem" title=3D"Gloria Steinem">Gloria Steinem</a>, spoke out in=
 favor of the ERA, arguing that ERA opposition was based on gender myths th=
at overemphasized difference and ignored evidence of unequal treatment betw=
een men and women.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-52"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> A more militant feminist group, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Grassroots_Group_of_Second_Class_Citizens" title=3D"Grassroots Group of Sec=
ond Class Citizens">Grassroots Group of Second Class Citizens</a>, organize=
d a series of non-violent direct action tactics in support of the ERA in Il=
linois in 1982.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-53"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It has been noted that many African-American women have supported th=
e ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SEDWICK_24=E2=80=9329_54-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-SE=
DWICK_24%E2%80%9329-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One prominent female supporter was New=
 York representative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shirley_Chish=
olm" title=3D"Shirley Chisholm">Shirley Chisholm</a>. On August 10, 1970, s=
he gave a speech on the ERA called "For the Equal Rights Amendment" in Wash=
ington, D.C. In her address, she claimed that sex discrimination had become=
 widespread and that the ERA would remedy it. She also claimed that laws to=
 protect women in the workforce from unsafe working conditions would be nee=
ded by men, too, and thus the ERA would help all people.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rig=
hts_Amendment#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By 1976, 60% of African-American wo=
men and 63% of African-American men were in favor of the ERA, and the legis=
lation was supported by organizations such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/National_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Colored_People"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"National Association for the Advancement of=
 Colored People">NAACP</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nation=
al_Council_of_Negro_Women" title=3D"National Council of Negro Women">Nation=
al Council of Negro Women</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coa=
lition_of_Black_Trade_Unionists" title=3D"Coalition of Black Trade Unionist=
s">Coalition of Black Trade Unionists</a>, National Association of Negro Bu=
siness, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Black_Fem=
inist_Organization" title=3D"National Black Feminist Organization">National=
 Black Feminist Organization</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SEDWICK_24=E2=80=9329_=
54-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Ri=
ghts_Amendment#cite_note-SEDWICK_24%E2%80%9329-54"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The ERA has been supported by several Republican women including <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florence_P._Dwyer" title=3D"Florence =
P. Dwyer">Florence Dwyer</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jill=
_Ruckelshaus" title=3D"Jill Ruckelshaus">Jill Ruckelshaus</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_D._Crisp" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Mary D. Crisp">Mary Dent Crisp</a>, Justice <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sandra_Day_O%27Connor" title=3D"Sandra Day O'Connor">Sandra Day O=
'Connor</a>, First Lady <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Ford=
" title=3D"Betty Ford">Betty Ford</a> and Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Chase_Smith" title=3D"Margaret Chase Smith">Margar=
et Chase Smith</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-56"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal=
_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Support from Republican men has=
 included President <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_D._Eise=
nhower" title=3D"Dwight D. Eisenhower">Dwight D. Eisenhower</a>, President =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Nixon" title=3D"Richard Ni=
xon">Richard Nixon</a>, Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ri=
chard_Lugar" title=3D"Richard Lugar">Richard Lugar</a> and Senator <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strom_Thurmond" title=3D"Strom Thurmond">=
Strom Thurmond</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ginsburg_1973_43-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_no=
te-Ginsburg_1973-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-'70s_245_24-4" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment=
#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_n=
ote-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-60"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_opposition">In oppositio=
n</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Righ=
ts_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: In =
opposition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Anti-ERA_women_dnd0215.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/9/96/Anti-ERA_women_dnd0215.jpg/250px-Anti-ERA_women_dnd0215.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"185" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"600" data-file-height=3D"444"></a><figcaption>Anti-ERA women wa=
tching a committee meeting of the Florida Senate in 1979, where considerati=
on of the ERA was postponed, thus effectively killing the resolution for th=
e 1979 session</figcaption></figure>
<p>Many opponents of the ERA focus on the importance of traditional gender =
roles. They argued that the amendment would guarantee the possibility that =
women would be subject to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conscrip=
tion_in_the_United_States" title=3D"Conscription in the United States">cons=
cription</a> and be required to have military combat roles in future wars i=
f it were passed. Defense of traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Gender_role" title=3D"Gender role">gender roles</a> proved to be a u=
seful tactic. In Illinois, supporters of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Phyllis_Schlafly" title=3D"Phyllis Schlafly">Phyllis Schlafly</a>, a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conservatism_in_the_United_States=
" title=3D"Conservatism in the United States">conservative</a> Republican a=
ctivist from Missouri, used traditional symbols of the American <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Housewife" title=3D"Housewife">housewife</a>.=
 They took homemade bread, jams, and apple pies to the state legislators, w=
ith the slogans, "Preserve us from a Congressional jam; Vote against the ER=
A sham" and "I am for Mom and apple pie."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rosenberg225_6=
2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rig=
hts_Amendment#cite_note-Rosenberg225-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They appealed to marri=
ed women by stressing that the amendment would invalidate protective laws s=
uch as alimony and eliminate the tendency for mothers to obtain custody ove=
r their children in divorce cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_not=
e-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> It was suggested that single-sex bathrooms would be elimi=
nated and same-sex couples would be able to get married if the amendment we=
re passed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-washingtonpost.com_64-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-w=
ashingtonpost.com-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Women who supported traditional gender ro=
les started to oppose the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-kllap_65-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite=
_note-kllap-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Schlafly said passage of the amendment would th=
reaten <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Security_(United_Sta=
tes)" title=3D"Social Security (United States)">Social Security</a> benefit=
s for housewives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-washingtonpost.com_64-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite=
_note-washingtonpost.com-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Opponents also argued that men and=
 women were already equal enough with the passage of the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Pay_Act_of_1963" title=3D"Equal Pay Act of 196=
3">Equal Pay Act of 1963</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964" title=3D"Civil Rights Act of 1964">Civil Right=
s Act of 1964</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-66"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> and that women's colleges would have to admit men. Schlafly's argument th=
at protective laws would be lost resonated with working-class women.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Activist_Phyllis_Schafly_weari=
ng_a_%22Stop_ERA%22_badge,_demonstrating_with_other_women_against_the_Equal=
_Rights_Amendment_in_front_of_the_White_House,_Washington,_D.C._(4221931409=
2).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Activist_Phyllis_Schafly_wearing_a_%22Stop=
_ERA%22_badge%2C_demonstrating_with_other_women_against_the_Equal_Rights_Am=
endment_in_front_of_the_White_House%2C_Washington%2C_D.C._%2842219314092%29=
.jpg/250px-thumbnail.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"210" height=3D"138" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4602" data-file-height=3D"3030"=
></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllis_Schlafly"=
 title=3D"Phyllis Schlafly">Phyllis Schlafly</a>, a conservative activist, =
organized opposition to the ERA and argued that it "would lead to women bei=
ng drafted by the military and to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Unisex_public_toilet" title=3D"Unisex public toilet">public unisex bathroom=
s</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-eilperin_68-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-eilperin-68"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>At the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1980_Republican_National=
_Convention" title=3D"1980 Republican National Convention">1980 Republican =
National Convention</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repub=
lican_Party_(United_States)" title=3D"Republican Party (United States)">Rep=
ublican Party</a> platform was amended to end its support for the ERA.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The most prominent op=
ponent of the ERA was Schlafly. Leading the Stop ERA campaign, Schlafly def=
ended traditional gender roles and would often attempt to incite feminists =
by opening her speeches with lines such as, "I'd like to thank my husband f=
or letting me be here tonight=E2=80=94I always like to say that, because it=
 makes the libs so mad."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-70"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> When Schlafly began her campaign in 1972, public polls showed suppo=
rt for the amendment was widely popular and thirty states had ratified the =
amendment by 1973. After 1973, the number of ratifying states slowed to a t=
rickle. Support in the states that had not ratified fell below 50%.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMansbridge214_71-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMansbri=
dge214-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Public opinion in key states shifted against the ERA=
 as its opponents, operating on the local and state levels, won over the pu=
blic. The state legislators in battleground states followed public opinion =
in rejecting the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECritchlow_and_Stachecki157=
_72-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_R=
ights_Amendment#cite_note-FOOTNOTECritchlow_and_Stachecki157-72"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Phyllis Schlafly was a key player in the defeat. Political scientist=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jane_Mansbridge" title=3D"Jane Ma=
nsbridge">Jane Mansbridge</a> in her history of the ERA argues that the dra=
ft issue was the single most powerful argument used by Schlafly and the oth=
er opponents to defeat ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-73"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Mansbridge concluded, "Many people who followed the struggle ove=
r the ERA believed=E2=80=94rightly in my view=E2=80=94that the Amendment wo=
uld have been ratified by 1975 or 1976 had it not been for Phyllis Schlafly=
's early and effective effort to organize potential opponents."<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTEMansbridge110_74-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMansbridge11=
0-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Legal scholar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo=
an_C._Williams" title=3D"Joan C. Williams">Joan C. Williams</a> maintained,=
 "ERA was defeated when Schlafly turned it into a war among women over gend=
er roles."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Histor=
ian Judith Glazer-Raymo asserted:
</p>
<blockquote><p>As moderates, we thought we represented the forces of reason=
 and goodwill but failed to take seriously the power of the family values a=
rgument and the single-mindedness of Schlafly and her followers. The ERA's =
defeat seriously damaged the women's movement, destroying its momentum and =
its potential to foment social change... Eventually, this resulted in femin=
ist dissatisfaction with the Republican Party, giving the Democrats a new s=
ource of strength that when combined with overwhelming minority support, he=
lped elect Bill Clinton to the presidency in 1992 and again in 1996.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Birch_Society" title=
=3D"John Birch Society">John Birch Society</a> and its members organized op=
position to the ERA in multiple states. According to Professor Edward H. Mi=
ller, the group played a key role in addition to Schlafly in preventing the=
 amendment's ratification.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Miller2021_77-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cit=
e_note-Miller2021-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many ERA supporters blamed their defeat on <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Advocacy_group" title=3D"Advocacy group">special interest</=
a> forces, especially the insurance industry and conservative organizations=
, suggesting that they had funded an opposition that subverted the democrat=
ic process and the will of the pro-ERA majority.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
ECritchlow_and_Stachecki157=E2=80=93158_78-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-FOOTNOTE=
Critchlow_and_Stachecki157%E2%80%93158-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such supporters argu=
ed that while the public face of the anti-ERA movement was Phyllis Schlafly=
 and her STOP ERA organization, there were other important groups in the op=
position as well, such as the powerful National Council of Catholic Women, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_feminism" title=3D"Labor fem=
inism">labor feminists</a><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fa=
ct" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span ti=
tle=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2018)">citatio=
n needed</span></a></i>]</sup> and (until 1973) the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/AFL%E2%80%93CIO" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"AFL=E2=80=
=93CIO">AFL=E2=80=93CIO</a>. Steinem blamed the insurance industry and said=
 Schlafly "did not change one vote."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_n=
ote-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Opposition to the amendment was particularly high among=
 religious conservatives, who argued that the amendment would guarantee uni=
versal abortion rights and the right for homosexual couples to marry.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Francis_ERA_History_80-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Francis_ERA_Hist=
ory-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-81"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Critchlow and Stachecki say the anti-ERA movement was based on strong ba=
cking among Southern whites, Evangelical Christians, members of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Sain=
ts" title=3D"The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints">the Church of=
 Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Orthodox_Judaism" title=3D"Orthodox Judaism">Orthodox Jews</a>, and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_Church_in_the_United_State=
s" title=3D"Catholic Church in the United States">Roman Catholics</a>, incl=
uding both men and women.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECritchlow_and_Stacheck=
i160_82-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equ=
al_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-FOOTNOTECritchlow_and_Stachecki160-82"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The ERA has long been opposed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Anti-abortion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anti-abortion">anti-abo=
rtion</a> groups who believe it would be interpreted to allow legal abortio=
n without limits and taxpayer funding for abortion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_A=
mendment#cite_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_n=
ote-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-85"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Public_opinion">Public opin=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Ri=
ghts_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: P=
ublic opinion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Public viewpoints on the amendment varied considerably by <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_regions_of_the_United_States" title=3D"L=
ist of regions of the United States">region</a>, with a poll from April 197=
5 finding 62 percent support in the East, and only 41 percent in the South.=
 The poll, conducted by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Harris=
_Poll" title=3D"The Harris Poll">Harris</a>, also found that men favored th=
e amendment 8% more than women did.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_no=
te-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
