<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Congressional_passage_(1970=
=E2=80=931972)"><span id=3D"Congressional_passage_.281970.E2.80.931972.29">=
</span>Congressional passage (1970=E2=80=931972)</h2><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Congressional passage (1970=E2=
=80=931972)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Martha_Griffiths.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c=
a/Martha_Griffiths.jpg/250px-Martha_Griffiths.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"190" height=3D"272" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"900" d=
ata-file-height=3D"1287"></a><figcaption>U.S. representative <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_W._Griffiths" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Martha W. Griffiths">Martha W. Griffiths</a> championed the ERA.</figca=
ption></figure>
<p>In February 1970, NOW picketed the United States Senate, a subcommittee =
of which was holding hearings on a constitutional amendment to lower the vo=
ting age to 18. NOW disrupted the hearings and demanded a hearing on the Eq=
ual Rights Amendment and won a meeting with senators to discuss the ERA. Th=
at August, over 20,000 American women held a nationwide <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Strike_for_Equality" title=3D"Women's Strik=
e for Equality">Women's Strike for Equality</a> protest to demand full soci=
al, economic, and political equality.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wommarch_87-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amen=
dment#cite_note-wommarch-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Said <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Betty_Friedan" title=3D"Betty Friedan">Betty Friedan</a> of the=
 strike, "All kinds of women's groups all over the country will be using th=
is week on August 26 particularly, to point out those areas in women's life=
 which are still not addressed. For example, a question of equality before =
the law; we are interested in the Equal Rights Amendment." Despite being ce=
ntered in New York City=E2=80=94which was regarded as one of the biggest st=
rongholds for NOW and other groups sympathetic to the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_liberation_movement" title=3D"Women's liberat=
ion movement">women's liberation movement</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redstockings" title=3D"Redstockings">Redstockings</a><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-femis209_88-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-femis209-88"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>=E2=80=94and having a small number of participants in contrast to the larg=
e-scale anti-war and civil rights protests that had occurred in the recent =
time prior to the event,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wommarch_87-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_no=
te-wommarch-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> the strike was credited as one of the biggest t=
urning points in the rise of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secon=
d-wave_feminism" title=3D"Second-wave feminism">second-wave feminism</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-femis209_88-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-femis209-88"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>In Washington, D.C., protesters presented a sympathetic Senate leade=
rship with a petition for the Equal Rights Amendment at the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Capitol" title=3D"United States Cap=
itol">U.S. Capitol</a>. Influential news sources such as <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_(magazine)" title=3D"Time (magazine)">Time</=
a></i> also supported the cause of the protestors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-womma=
rch_87-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equa=
l_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-wommarch-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Soon after the strike=
 took place, activists distributed literature across the country as well.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-femis209_88-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-femis209-88"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In 1970, congressional hearings began on the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-89" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_A=
mendment#cite_note-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On August 10, 1970, Michigan Democrat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Martha_Griffiths" title=3D"Martha Griffiths">Martha Griffiths</a=
> successfully brought the Equal Rights Amendment to the House floor, after=
 15 years of the joint resolution having languished in the House Judiciary =
Committee. The joint resolution passed in the House and continued on to the=
 Senate, which voted for the ERA with an added clause that women would be e=
xempt from the military. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/91st_=
United_States_Congress" title=3D"91st United States Congress">91st Congress=
</a>, however, ended before the joint resolution could progress any further=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-90" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Griffiths reintroduced the ERA, and achieved success on Capitol Hill=
 with her H.J.Res.&nbsp;208, which was adopted by the House on October 12, =
1971, with a vote of 354 yeas (For), 24 nays (Against) and 51 not voting.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-92" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rig=
hts_Amendment#cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Griffiths's joint resolution was th=
en adopted by the Senate=E2=80=94without change=E2=80=94on March 22, 1972, =
by a vote of 84 yeas, 8 nays and 7 not voting.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-94" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-94"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> The Senate version, drafted by Senator <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Birch_Bayh" title=3D"Birch Bayh">Birch Bayh</a> of Indian=
a,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-95" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> passed after t=
he defeat of an amendment proposed by Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sam_Ervin" title=3D"Sam Ervin">Sam Ervin</a> of North Carolina =
that would have exempted women from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Conscription" title=3D"Conscription">draft</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-'7=
0s_245_24-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
qual_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-96" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rig=
hts_Amendment#cite_note-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> President <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Nixon" title=3D"Richard Nixon">Richard Nixon</a> im=
mediately endorsed the ERA's approval upon its passage by the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/92nd_United_States_Congress" title=3D"92nd Unit=
ed States Congress">92nd Congress</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-'70s_245_24-6" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Ame=
ndment#cite_note-'70s_245-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
