<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Rescinding_ratification">Re=
scinding ratification</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=
=3D"Edit section: Rescinding ratification"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Six state legislatures (noted above) have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Repeal#Legislative_use" title=3D"Repeal">rescinded</a> their ear=
lier ratification of the ERA. Article V of the Constitution is silent as to=
 whether a state may rescind, or otherwise revoke, a previous ratification =
of a proposed constitutional amendment while it is pending before the state=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The rescind=
ing of a ratification of a constitutional amendment has occurred previously=
. In the 1860s, a few states voted to rescind their ratifications for the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourteenth_Amendment_to_the_United_=
States_Constitution" title=3D"Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Con=
stitution">Fourteenth</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fift=
eenth_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Fifteenth Amend=
ment to the United States Constitution">Fifteenth</a> Amendments. On both o=
ccasions however, these actions were rejected and the original ratification=
 was counted when the federal government tallied the total states that had =
ratified the amendment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_116-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-:3-=
116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-117" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-117"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>In February 2024, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ameri=
can_Bar_Association" title=3D"American Bar Association">American Bar Associ=
ation</a> (ABA) passed resolution 601, supporting implementation of the ERA=
. The ABA urges implementation stating that a deadline for ratification of =
an amendment to the U.S. Constitution is not consistent with Article V of t=
he Constitution and that under Article V, states are not permitted to resci=
nd prior ratifications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-118" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-118"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>Researchers at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbia_Law=
_School" title=3D"Columbia Law School">Columbia Law School</a>'s Center for=
 Gender and Sexuality Law have written that "[t]he Constitution says nothin=
g about whether a state can rescind or revoke its ratification of a Constit=
utional Amendment, either before the ratification process has been complete=
d or after." Advocates and scholars dispute whether ratification is a one-t=
ime event, once done it cannot be undone as the Constitution only provides =
for ratification, not unratification.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_116-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment=
#cite_note-:3-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sunsetting_ratifications">S=
unsetting ratifications</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Sunsetting ratifications"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"South_Dakota_(pre-1979_dead=
line)"><span id=3D"South_Dakota_.28pre-1979_deadline.29"></span>South Dakot=
a (pre-1979 deadline)</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: South Dakota (pre-1979 deadline)"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Among those rejecting Congress's claim to even hold authority to extend =
a previously established ratification deadline, the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/South_Dakota_Legislature" title=3D"South Dakota Legislatu=
re">South Dakota Legislature</a> adopted Senate Joint Resolution No. 2 on M=
arch 1, 1979. The joint resolution stipulated that South Dakota's 1973 ERA =
ratification would be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunset_provi=
sion" title=3D"Sunset provision">"sunsetted"</a> as of the original deadlin=
e, March 22, 1979. South Dakota's 1979 sunset joint resolution declared: "t=
he Ninety-fifth Congress ex post facto has sought unilaterally to alter the=
 terms and conditions in such a way as to materially affect the congression=
ally established time period for ratification" (designated as "POM-93" by t=
he U.S. Senate and published verbatim in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Congressional_Record" title=3D"Congressional Record">Congress=
ional Record</a></i> of March 13, 1979, at pages 4861 and 4862).<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The action on the part of South Dakota lawmakers=E2=80=94occurring 2=
1 days prior to originally agreed-upon deadline of March 22, 1979=E2=80=94c=
ould be viewed as slightly different from a rescission.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
120" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rig=
hts_Amendment#cite_note-120"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/The_Constitution_of_the_United_States_of_America:_Analysis_and_Inte=
rpretation" title=3D"The Constitution of the United States of America: Anal=
ysis and Interpretation"><i>Constitution Annotated</i></a> notes that "[f]o=
ur states had rescinded their ratifications [of the ERA] and a fifth had de=
clared that its ratification would be void unless the amendment was ratifie=
d within the original time limit", with a footnote identifying South Dakota=
 as that "fifth" state.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-121"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"North_Dakota_(post-1979_dea=
dline)"><span id=3D"North_Dakota_.28post-1979_deadline.29"></span>North Dak=
ota (post-1979 deadline)</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index=
.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: North Dakota (post-1979 deadline)"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On March 19, 2021, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Dakota=
_Legislative_Assembly" title=3D"North Dakota Legislative Assembly">North Da=
kota state lawmakers</a> adopted Senate Concurrent Resolution No. 4010 to r=
etroactively clarify that North Dakota's 1975 ratification of the ERA was v=
alid only through "11:59 p.m. on March 22, 1979" and went on to proclaim th=
at North Dakota "should not be counted by Congress, the Archivist of the Un=
ited States, lawmakers in any other state, any court of law, or any other p=
erson, as still having on record a live ratification of the proposed Equal =
Rights Amendment to the Constitution of the United States as was offered by=
 House Joint Resolution No. 208 of the 92nd Congress on March 22, 1972".<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-122" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The resolution w=
as formally received by the U.S. Senate on April 20, 2021, was designated a=
s "POM-10", was referred to the Senate's Judiciary Committee, and its full =
and complete verbatim text was published at page S2066 of the <i>Congressio=
nal Record</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-123" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-123"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Ratification_deadline_and_e=
xtension">Ratification deadline and extension</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Ratification deadline and extensio=
n"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Congressional_action">Congr=
essional action</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Congressional action"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The original joint resolution (H.J.Res.&nbsp;208), by which the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/92nd_United_States_Congress" title=3D"92n=
d United States Congress">92nd Congress</a> proposed the amendment to the s=
tates, was prefaced by the following resolving clause:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Resolved by the Senate a=
nd House of Representatives of the United States of America in Congress ass=
embled (two-thirds of each House concurring therein), That the following ar=
ticle is proposed as an amendment to the Constitution of the United States,=
 which shall be valid to all intents and purposes as part of the Constituti=
on when ratified by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several States=
 <i>within seven years from the date of its submission by the Congress</i>:=
 [emphasis added]</p></blockquote>
<p>As the joint resolution was passed on March 22, 1972, this effectively s=
et March 22, 1979, as the deadline for the amendment to be ratified by the =
requisite number of states. However, the 92nd Congress did not incorporate =
any time limit into the body of the actual text of the proposed amendment, =
as had been done with a number of other proposed amendments.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equa=
l_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1978, as the original 1979 deadline approached, the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/95th_United_States_Congress" title=3D"95th Unit=
ed States Congress">95th Congress</a> adopted <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"=
external text" href=3D"https://www.congress.gov/bill/95th-congress/house-jo=
int-resolution/638">H.J.Res.&nbsp;638</a>, by Representative <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Holtzman" title=3D"Elizabeth Holtzman"=
>Elizabeth Holtzman</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Yor=
k_(state)" title=3D"New York (state)">New York</a> (House: August; Senate: =
October 6; signing of the President: October 20), which purported to extend=
 the ERA's ratification deadline to June 30, 1982.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_A=
mendment#cite_note-125"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> H.J.Res. 638 received less than two-th=
irds of the vote (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Majority" titl=
e=3D"Majority">simple majority</a>, not a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Supermajority" title=3D"Supermajority">supermajority</a>) in both t=
he House of Representatives and the Senate; for that reason, ERA supporters=
 deemed it necessary that H.J.Res. 638 be transmitted to then-President <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Carter" title=3D"Jimmy Carter">=
Jimmy Carter</a> for signature as a safety precaution. The <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Supre=
me Court of the United States">U.S. Supreme Court</a> ruled in <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hollingsworth_v._Virginia" title=3D"Holli=
ngsworth v. Virginia">Hollingsworth v. Virginia</a></i> (1798)<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Hollingsworth_v._Virginia_volume=3D3_page=3D378_year=3D1798_126-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Am=
endment#cite_note-Hollingsworth_v._Virginia_volume=3D3_page=3D378_year=3D17=
98-126"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pres=
ident_of_the_United_States" title=3D"President of the United States">Presid=
ent of the United States</a> has no formal role in the passing of constitut=
ional amendments. Carter signed the joint resolution, although he noted, on=
 strictly procedural grounds, the irregularity of his doing so given the Su=
preme Court's decision in 1798. During this disputed extension of slightly =
more than three years, no additional states ratified or <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_rescissions_of_Article_V_Convention_applicati=
ons" title=3D"List of rescissions of Article V Convention applications">res=
cinded</a>.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Photograph_of_Jimmy_Carter_Signing_Extension_=
of_Equal_Rights_Amendment_(ERA)_Ratification,_10-20-1978.jpg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/b/b3/Photograph_of_Jimmy_Carter_Signing_Extension_of_Equal_Rights_Am=
endment_%28ERA%29_Ratification%2C_10-20-1978.jpg/330px-Photograph_of_Jimmy_=
Carter_Signing_Extension_of_Equal_Rights_Amendment_%28ERA%29_Ratification%2=
C_10-20-1978.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"210" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3000" data-file-height=3D"2032"></a><fi=
gcaption>President Carter signing <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external tex=
t" href=3D"https://www.congress.gov/bill/95th-congress/house-joint-resoluti=
on/638">H.J.Res.&nbsp;638</a> on October 20, 1978</figcaption></figure>
<p>The purported extension of ERA's ratification deadline was vigorously co=
ntested in 1978 as scholars were divided as to whether Congress actually ha=
s authority to revise a previously agreed-to deadline for the states to act=
 upon a constitutional amendment. On June 18, 1980, a resolution in the Ill=
inois House of Representatives resulted in a vote of 102=E2=80=9371 in favo=
r, but Illinois' internal parliamentary rules required a three-fifths major=
ity on constitutional amendments and so the measure failed by five votes. I=
n 1982, seven female ERA supporters, known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Grassroots_Group_of_Second_Class_Citizens" title=3D"Grassro=
ots Group of Second Class Citizens">Grassroots Group of Second Class Citize=
ns</a>, went on a fast known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wo=
men_Hunger_for_Justice" title=3D"Women Hunger for Justice">Women Hunger for=
 Justice</a> and seventeen chained themselves to the entrance of the Illino=
is Senate chamber.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-127" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-127"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-hungryheart_128-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-hungryheart-1=
28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-nytimes-era_129-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-n=
ytimes-era-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>128<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonia=
_Johnson" title=3D"Sonia Johnson">Sonia Johnson</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoe_Nicholson" title=3D"Zoe Nicholson">Zoe Nicholson</a>=
 and Sister <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maureen_Fiedler" title=
=3D"Maureen Fiedler">Maureen Feidler</a> all participated in the fast.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-130" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-131" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Ri=
ghts_Amendment#cite_note-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The closest that the ERA came to=
 gaining an additional ratification between the original deadline of March =
22, 1979, and the revised June 30, 1982, expiration date was when it was ap=
proved by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_House_of_Rep=
resentatives" title=3D"Florida House of Representatives">Florida House of R=
epresentatives</a> on June 21, 1982. In the final week before the revised d=
eadline, that ratifying resolution, however, was defeated in the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_Senate" title=3D"Florida Senate">Flo=
rida Senate</a> by a vote of 16 to 22. Even if Florida had ratified the ERA=
, the proposed amendment would still have fallen short of the required 38. =
Many ERA supporters mourned the failure of the amendment. For example, a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jazz_funeral_for_the_ERA" title=3D"J=
azz funeral for the ERA">jazz funeral for the ERA</a> was held in New Orlea=
ns in July 1982.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-132" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-132"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>According to research by Jules B. Gerard, professor of law at <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_University_in_St._Louis" titl=
e=3D"Washington University in St. Louis">Washington University in St. Louis=
</a>, of the 35 legislatures that passed ratification resolutions, 24 of th=
em explicitly referred to the original 1979 deadline.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Right=
s_Amendment#cite_note-133"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>132<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templat=
e" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title=
=3D"Letters are usually not verifiable. Was this published? If so, how/wher=
e? (January 2025)">verification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lawsuit_regarding_deadline_=
extension">Lawsuit regarding deadline extension</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Lawsuit regarding deadline exten=
sion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>On December 23, 1981, a federal district court, in the case of <i>Idaho =
v. Freeman</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-134" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-134"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>133<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> ruled that the extension of the ERA ratification deadline to June 30, 198=
2, was not valid, and that the ERA had actually expired from state legislat=
ive consideration more than two years earlier on the original expiration da=
te of March 22, 1979.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freeman_135-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-=
Freeman-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>134<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> On January 25, 1982, however, the U.S. Supreme Co=
urt <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stay_of_proceedings" title=3D"=
Stay of proceedings">stayed</a> the lower court's decision.
</p><p>After the disputed June 30, 1982, extended deadline had come and gon=
e, the Supreme Court, at the beginning of its new term, on October 4, 1982,=
 in the separate case of <i>NOW v. Idaho</i>, 459 U.S. 809 (1982),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-136" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-136"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>135<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> vacated the federal =
district court decision in <i>Idaho v. Freeman</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Free=
man_135-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equ=
al_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Freeman-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>134<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which, in addition =
to declaring March 22, 1979, as ERA's expiration date, had upheld the valid=
ity of state rescissions. The Supreme Court declared these controversies <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mootness" title=3D"Mootness">moot</a=
> based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memorandum" title=
=3D"Memorandum">memorandum</a> of the appellant Gerald P. Carmen, the then-=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Administrator_of_General_Services"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Administrator of General Services">Administ=
rator of General Services</a>, that the ERA had not received the required n=
umber of ratifications (38) and so "the Amendment has failed of adoption no=
 matter what the resolution of the legal issues presented here".<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-ef-nvi_137-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-ef-nvi-137"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-138" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-138"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>137<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1939 case of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cole=
man_v._Miller" title=3D"Coleman v. Miller">Coleman v. Miller</a></i>, the S=
upreme Court ruled that if there was not a deadline by which the proposed a=
mendment had to be acted upon by the requisite three-fourths of state legis=
latures or state ratifying conventions, then the proposed amendment remains=
. The court also ruled that it is in the discretion of Congress to arbitrat=
e whether at least three-fourths of the states have ratified that amendment=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Lawsuits_regarding_ratifica=
tion">Lawsuits regarding ratification</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Lawsuits regarding ratification"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alabama_lawsuit_opposing_ra=
tification">Alabama lawsuit opposing ratification</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Alabama lawsuit opposing ratif=
ication"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>On December 16, 2019, the states of Alabama, Louisiana and South Dakota =
sued to prevent further ratifying of the Equal Rights Amendment. <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alabama_Attorney_General" title=3D"Alabama A=
ttorney General">Alabama Attorney General</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Steve_Marshall_(politician)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ste=
ve Marshall (politician)">Steve Marshall</a> stated, "The people had seven =
years to consider the ERA, and they rejected it. To sneak it into the Const=
itution through this illegal process would undermine the very basis for our=
 constitutional order."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-139" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-139"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>South Dakota Attorney General <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Jason_Ravnsborg" title=3D"Jason Ravnsborg">Jason Ravnsborg</a> stated in=
 a press release:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-140" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-140"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>139<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The South Dakota Legisla=
ture ratified the ERA in 1973, but in 1979 passed Senate Joint Resolution 2=
 which required the ERA be ratified in the original time limit set by Congr=
ess or be rescinded. Because thirty-eight states failed to ratify the amend=
ment by March 31, 1979 the South Dakota Legislature rescinded its ratificat=
ion of the ERA. It is the duty of the Attorney General to defend and suppor=
t our Legislature. It would be a disservice to the citizens of South Dakota=
 to ignore this obligation of my office.
This is an issue of following the rule of law, the rules that our founding =
fathers put into place to protect us from government making decisions witho=
ut the consent or support of "we the people". If Congress wants to pass an =
updated version of the ERA, taking into consideration all the changes in th=
e law since 1972, I have no doubt the South Dakota Legislature would debate=
 the merits in a new ratification process. An amendment to the Constitution=
 should not be done by procedural nuances decades after the deadline prescr=
ibed by Congress, but through an open and transparent process where each St=
ate knows the ramifications of its actions.</p></blockquote>
<p>On January 6, 2020, the Department of Justice <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Office_of_Legal_Counsel" title=3D"Office of Legal Counsel">O=
ffice of Legal Counsel</a> official Steven Engel issued an opinion in respo=
nse to the lawsuit by Alabama, Louisiana, and South Dakota, stating that "W=
e conclude that Congress had the constitutional authority to impose a deadl=
ine on the ratification of the ERA and, because that deadline has expired, =
the ERA Resolution is no longer pending before the States."<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-141" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal=
_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-141"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>140<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The OLC argued in part that C=
ongress had the authority to impose a deadline for the ERA and that it did =
not have the authority to retroactively extend the deadline once it had exp=
ired.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-142" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-142"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>141<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On February 27, 2020, the States of Alabama, Louisiana and South Dak=
ota entered into a joint stipulation and voluntary dismissal with the Archi=
vist of the United States. The joint stipulation incorporated the Departmen=
t of Justice's Office of Legal Counsel's opinion; stated that the Archivist=
 would not certify the adoption of the Equal Rights Amendment and stated th=
at if the Department of Justice ever concludes that the 1972 ERA Resolution=
 is still pending and that the Archivist therefore has authority to certify=
 the ERA's adoption ... the Archivist will make no certification concerning=
 ratification of the ERA until at least 45 days following the announcement =
of the Department of Justice's conclusion, absent a court order compelling =
him to do so sooner."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-143" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-143"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> On March 2, 2020, Federal District Court Judge <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L._Scott_Coogler" title=3D"L. Scott Coogler">L. Scot=
t Coogler</a> entered an order regarding the Joint Stipulation and Plaintif=
f's Voluntary Dismissal, granting the dismissal without prejudice.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-144" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-144"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>143<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Massachusetts_lawsuit_suppo=
rting_ratification">Massachusetts lawsuit supporting ratification</h3><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendmen=
t&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Massachusetts =
lawsuit supporting ratification"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On January 7, 2020, a complaint was filed by Equal Means Equal, The Yell=
ow Roses and Katherine Weitbrecht in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_District_of_Massachusetts" titl=
e=3D"United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts">United=
 States District Court for the District of Massachusetts</a> against the Ar=
chivist of the United States, seeking to have him count the three most rece=
ntly ratifying states and certify the ERA as having become part of the Unit=
ed States Constitution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-145" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-145"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> On August 6, 2020, Judge <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Denise_Casper" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Denise Casper">Denise Casper=
</a> granted the Archivist's motion to dismiss, ruling that the plaintiffs =
did not have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standing_(law)" title=
=3D"Standing (law)">standing</a> to sue to compel the Archivist to certify =
and so she could not rule on the merits of the case.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-146=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights=
_Amendment#cite_note-146"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>145<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On August 21, 2020, the plaintiffs a=
ppealed this decision to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unite=
d_States_Court_of_Appeals_for_the_First_Circuit" title=3D"United States Cou=
rt of Appeals for the First Circuit">United States Court of Appeals for the=
 First Circuit</a> and on September 2, 2020, the plaintiffs asked the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" tit=
le=3D"Supreme Court of the United States">Supreme Court</a> to hear this ca=
se.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-147" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-147"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>146<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-148" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-148"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
147<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Subsequently, the Suprem=
e Court denied the request to intervene before the First Circuit gives its =
decision.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-149"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>148<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-150" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-150"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>149<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  On June 29, 2021,=
 the First Circuit affirmed the District Court's decision that "the plainti=
ffs have not met their burden at the pleading stage with respect to those f=
ederal constitutional requirements; we affirm the order dismissing their su=
it for lack of standing."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-151" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-151"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>150<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> An <i>en banc</i> rehearing request was denied on January 4, 20=
22.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-152" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-152"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>151<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"2020=E2=80=932023_lawsuit_i=
n_the_District_of_Columbia_supporting_ratification"><span id=3D"2020.E2.80.=
932023_lawsuit_in_the_District_of_Columbia_supporting_ratification"></span>=
2020=E2=80=932023 lawsuit in the District of Columbia supporting ratificati=
on</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rig=
hts_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: 20=
20=E2=80=932023 lawsuit in the District of Columbia supporting ratification=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>On January 30, 2020, the attorneys general of Virginia, Illinois and Nev=
ada filed a lawsuit in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_=
States_District_Court_for_the_District_of_Columbia" title=3D"United States =
District Court for the District of Columbia">United States District Court f=
or the District of Columbia</a> to require the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Archivist_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Archivist of the Unit=
ed States">Archivist of the United States</a> to "carry out his statutory d=
uty of recognizing the complete and final adoption" of the ERA as the Twent=
y-eighth Amendment to the Constitution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-153" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#ci=
te_note-153"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>152<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
On February 19, 2020, the States of Alabama, Louisiana, Nebraska, South Dak=
ota and Tennessee moved to intervene in the case.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-154" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Am=
endment#cite_note-154"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>153<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On March 10, 2020, the Plaintiff State=
s (Virginia, Illinois and Nevada) filed a memorandum in opposition to the f=
ive states seeking to intervene.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-155" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note=
-155"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>154<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> On May 7, 2020, the DOJ filed a motion to dismiss, claim=
ing the states do not have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standin=
g_(law)" title=3D"Standing (law)">standing</a> to bring the case to trial a=
s they have to show any "concrete injury", nor that the case was <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ripeness" title=3D"Ripeness">ripe</a> for re=
view.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-156" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-156"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>155<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On June 12, 2020, the District Court granted the Intervening states =
(Alabama, Louisiana, Nebraska, South Dakota and Tennessee) motion to interv=
ene in the case.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-157" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-157"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>156<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> On March 5, 2021, federal judge <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rudolph_Contreras" title=3D"Rudolph Contreras">Rudolph Contreras</a> of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for=
_the_District_of_Columbia" title=3D"United States District Court for the Di=
strict of Columbia">United States District Court for the District of Columb=
ia</a> ruled that the ratification period for the ERA "expired long ago" an=
d that three states' recent ratifications had come too late to be counted i=
n the amendment's favor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-158" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-158"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>157<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-159" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-159"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>158<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On May 3, 2021, the plaintiff states appealed the ruling to the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Court_of_Appeals_for_the=
_District_of_Columbia_Circuit" title=3D"United States Court of Appeals for =
the District of Columbia Circuit">United States Court of Appeals for the Di=
strict of Columbia Circuit</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-160" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-=
160"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Virginia withdrew from the lawsuit in February 2022.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-161" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-161"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>160<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Oral arguments wer=
e held on September 28, 2022,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-162" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-16=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>161<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> before a panel composed by judges <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Robert_L._Wilkins" title=3D"Robert L. Wilkins">Wilkins</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neomi_Rao" title=3D"Neomi Rao">Ra=
o</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._Michelle_Childs" titl=
e=3D"J. Michelle Childs">Childs</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-163" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_=
note-163"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>162<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> On February 28, 2023, the panel ruled that the plain=
tiffs failed to prove the ERA deadline invalid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-164" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amen=
dment#cite_note-164"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>163<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-165" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_not=
e-165"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>164<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"2023=E2=80=932025_Californi=
a_lawsuit_supporting_ratification"><span id=3D"2023.E2.80.932025_California=
_lawsuit_supporting_ratification"></span>2023=E2=80=932025 California lawsu=
it supporting ratification</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28"=
 title=3D"Edit section: 2023=E2=80=932025 California lawsuit supporting rat=
ification"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>On June 23, 2023, Vikram Valame filed a complaint against the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selective_Service_System" title=3D"Selective=
 Service System">Selective Service System</a> for harms caused by the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_Selective_Service_Act" title=
=3D"Military Selective Service Act">Military Selective Service Act</a>. The=
 plaintiff argued that he was "subject to criminal prosecution, fines and i=
mprisonment" under "unconstitutional registration and reporting requirement=
s" and denied "valuable educational and job opportunities" due to failure t=
o register.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-166" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-166"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>165<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Va=
lame argued that the ERA had been validly ratified as the 28th Amendment to=
 the Constitution, contending that Congress's deadline for ratification was=
 unconstitutional under Article V and that states had no ability to revoke =
their ratifications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-167" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-167"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>On January 20, 2024, Judge Nathanael M. Cousins granted the defendan=
ts' motion to dismiss and denied the plaintiff's motion for summary judgmen=
t. The court ruled that "no 28th Amendment appears in the Constitution" and=
 that the plaintiff "cannot state a claim for relief under a constitutional=
 amendment that does not exist."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-168" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note=
-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>167<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Valame filed a notice of appeal to the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninth_Circuit_Court_of_Appeals" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals">Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-169" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-169"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>168<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On July 1=
7, 2025, the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed the dismissal of Valam=
e's complaint, saying, "We reject as meritless Valame=E2=80=99s contention =
that the Equal Rights Amendment was ratified as the Twenty-Eighth Amendment=
 to the Constitution."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-170" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-170"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>169<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Post-deadline_history">Post=
-deadline history</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"E=
dit section: Post-deadline history"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Post-deadline_ratifications=
_and_the_&quot;three-state_strategy&quot;"><span id=3D"Post-deadline_ratifi=
cations_and_the_.22three-state_strategy.22"></span>Post-deadline ratificati=
ons and the "three-state strategy"</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Post-deadline ratifications and the &quot;thr=
ee-state strategy&quot;"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Beginning in the mid-1990s, ERA supporters began an effort to win ratifi=
cation of the ERA by the legislatures of states that did not ratify it betw=
een 1972 and 1982. These proponents state that Congress can remove the ERA'=
s ratification deadline despite the deadline having expired, allowing the s=
tates again to ratify it. They also state that the ratifications ERA previo=
usly received remain in force and that rescissions of prior ratifications a=
re not valid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-171" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-171"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>170<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Those who espouse the "three-state strategy" (now complete if the Nevada,=
 Illinois and Virginia belated ERA approvals are deemed legitimate) were sp=
urred, at least in part, by the unconventional 202-year-long ratification o=
f the Constitution's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twenty-sevent=
h_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Twenty-seventh Amen=
dment to the United States Constitution">Twenty-seventh Amendment</a> (some=
times referred to as the "Madison Amendment") which became part of the Cons=
titution in 1992 after pending before the state legislatures since 1789. Ho=
wever, the "Madison Amendment" was not associated with a ratification deadl=
ine, whereas the proposing clause of the ERA did include a deadline.
</p><p>On June 21, 2009, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natio=
nal_Organization_for_Women" title=3D"National Organization for Women">Natio=
nal Organization for Women</a> decided to support both efforts to obtain ad=
ditional state ratifications for the 1972 ERA and any strategy to submit a =
fresh-start ERA to the states for ratification.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-172" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amen=
dment#cite_note-172"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>171<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>
In 2013, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_of_Congress" =
title=3D"Library of Congress">Library of Congress</a>'s <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congressional_Research_Service" title=3D"Congressiona=
l Research Service">Congressional Research Service</a> issued a report sayi=
ng that ratification deadlines are a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Political_question" title=3D"Political question">political question</a>:=
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"></p><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>ERA proponents claim=
 that the Supreme Court's decision in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Coleman_v._Miller" title=3D"Coleman v. Miller">Coleman v. Miller</a>=
</i> gives Congress wide discretion in setting conditions for the ratificat=
ion process.</p></blockquote><p> The report goes on to say:<link rel=3D"mw-=
deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1244412712"></p>=
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Revivification opponents caution ERA=
 supporters against an overly broad interpretation of <i>Coleman v. Miller<=
/i>, which, they argue, may have been be  [<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sic" title=3D"Sic">sic</a></i>] a politically influenced decisi=
on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-173" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-173"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>172<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></block=
quote>
<p>However, most recently, ERA Action has both led and brought renewed vigo=
r to the movement by instituting what has become known as the "three-state =
strategy".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-174" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-174"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>173<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In =
2013, ERA Action began to gain traction with this strategy through their co=
ordination with U.S. Senators and Representatives not only to introduce leg=
islation in both houses of Congress to remove the ratification deadline, bu=
t also in gaining legislative sponsors. The Congressional Research Service =
then issued a report on the "three state strategy" on April 8, 2013, entitl=
ed "The Proposed Equal Rights Amendment: Contemporary Ratification Issues",=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-175" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-175"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>174<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> stating that =
the approach was viable.
</p><p>In 2014, under the auspices of ERA Action and their coalition partne=
rs, both the Virginia and Illinois state senates voted to ratify the ERA. T=
hat year, votes were blocked in both states' House chambers. In the meantim=
e, the ERA ratification movement continued with the resolution being introd=
uced in 10 state legislatures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-176" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-1=
76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>175<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35_years_after_177-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_not=
e-35_years_after-177"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>176<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-178" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_=
note-178"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>177<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 2010s, due in part to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Fourth-wave_feminism" title=3D"Fourth-wave feminism">fourth-wave feminism=
</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MeToo_movement" title=
=3D"MeToo movement">#MeToo movement</a>, observers noted a renewed interest=
 in adoption of the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-179" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-179"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>178<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-180" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-180"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>179<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On March 22, 2017, the Nevada Legislature became the first state in =
40 years to ratify the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35_years_after2_181-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-35_years_after2-181"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>180=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-182" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amen=
dment#cite_note-182"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>181<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Illinois lawmakers and citizens took another look at the ERA, with h=
earings, testimony, and research including work by the law firm Winston &am=
p; Strawn to address common legal questions about the ERA.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-183" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_=
Rights_Amendment#cite_note-183"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>182<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Illinois state lawmakers ratified the ERA on May 30, 2018, with a 72=
=E2=80=9345 vote in the Illinois House following a 43=E2=80=9312 vote in th=
e Illinois Senate in April 2018.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-184" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note=
-184"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>183<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-185" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-185"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>184<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Virginia became the 38th state to ratify the Equal Rights Amendment =
in January of 2020.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-186" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-186"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>185<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-187" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-187"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>186<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-188" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-188"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>187<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Prior, an effort to =
ratify the ERA in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virginia_Gen=
eral_Assembly" title=3D"Virginia General Assembly">Virginia General Assembl=
y</a> in 2018 failed to reach the floor of either the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virginia_House_of_Delegates" title=3D"Virginia House of=
 Delegates">House of Delegates</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Virginia_Senate" title=3D"Virginia Senate">Senate</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-189" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_=
Rights_Amendment#cite_note-189"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>188<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-190" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-190"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>189<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-191" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-=
191"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>190<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> In 2019, a Senate committee voted to advance the ERA to t=
he floor. On January 15, the Senate voted 26=E2=80=9314 to approve the amen=
dment and forward it to the House of Delegates, but it was defeated there i=
n a 50=E2=80=9350 tied vote; at the time, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title=3D"Republican Party (Un=
ited States)">Republican Party</a> held one-seat majorities in both houses.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-192" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-192"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>191<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> After the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Virginia_elections" title=3D"201=
9 Virginia elections">2019 elections in Virginia</a> gave the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)" title=3D"Demo=
cratic Party (United States)">Democratic Party</a> majority control of both=
 houses of the Virginia legislature, the incoming leaders expressed their i=
ntent to hold another vote on ratification early in the 2020 legislative se=
ssion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_193-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-:1-193"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>192<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> They did so, with ERA ratification resolutions HJ1 and SJ1 being passed i=
n their respective chambers on January 15, 2020, and being passed by each o=
ther on January 27.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-194" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-194"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>193<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Experts and advocates have acknowledged the legal uncertainty of the =
Virginian ratification, due to the expired deadlines and five revocations.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Virginia2_195-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Virginia2-195"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>194<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>On December 15, 2024, a group of over 120 Democrats in the House of =
Representatives, led by Representatives <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Cori_Bush" title=3D"Cori Bush">Cori Bush</a> (D-Missouri) and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayanna_Pressley" title=3D"Ayanna Pressley=
">Ayanna Pressley</a> (D-Massachusetts), sent a letter to outgoing Presiden=
t <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden" title=3D"Joe Biden">J=
oe Biden</a>, arguing that both the deadlines and the revocations were ille=
gitimate, meaning the ERA had been successfully ratified by 38 states, and =
urging Biden to direct the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archivi=
st_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Archivist of the United States">Archivist=
 of the United States</a> to certify the amendment as part of the Constitut=
ion immediately.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-196" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-196"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>195<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Reintroduction_of_the_amend=
ment_in_Congress">Reintroduction of the amendment in Congress</h3><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Reintroduction of =
the amendment in Congress"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The amendment has been reintroduced in every session of Congress since 1=
982. Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Kennedy" title=3D=
"Ted Kennedy">Ted Kennedy</a> (D-Massachusetts) championed it in the Senate=
 from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/99th_United_States_Congr=
ess" title=3D"99th United States Congress">99th Congress</a> through the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/110th_United_States_Congress" title=
=3D"110th United States Congress">110th Congress</a>. Senator <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Menendez" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Robert Menendez">Robert Menendez</a> (D-New Jersey) introduced the amendme=
nt at the end of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/111th_United_=
States_Congress" title=3D"111th United States Congress">111th Congress</a> =
and supported it in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/112th_Unit=
ed_States_Congress" title=3D"112th United States Congress">112th Congress</=
a>. In the House of Representatives, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Carolyn_Maloney" title=3D"Carolyn Maloney">Carolyn Maloney</a> (D-New Yo=
rk) has sponsored it since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/105=
th_United_States_Congress" title=3D"105th United States Congress">105th Con=
gress</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-197" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-197"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>196<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> mos=
t recently in August 2013.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-198" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-198">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>197<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1983, the ERA passed through House committees with the same text =
as in 1972; however, it failed by six votes to achieve the necessary two-th=
irds vote on the House floor. That was the last time that the ERA received =
a floor vote in either house of Congress.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-199" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#=
cite_note-199"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>198<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>At the start of the 112th Congress on January 6, 2011, Senator Menen=
dez, along with representatives Maloney, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Jerrold_Nadler" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jerrold Nadler">Jerro=
ld Nadler</a> (D-New York) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwe=
n_Moore" title=3D"Gwen Moore">Gwen Moore</a> (D-Wisconsin), held a press co=
nference advocating for the Equal Rights Amendment's adoption.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-200" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eq=
ual_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-200"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On March 5, 2013, the ERA =
was reintroduced by Senator Menendez as S.J. Res. 10.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Right=
s_Amendment#cite_note-201"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>200<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The "New ERA" introduced in 2013, sponsored by Representative Caroly=
n B. Maloney, adds an additional sentence to the original text: "Women shal=
l have equal rights in the United States and every place subject to its jur=
isdiction."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-202" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-202"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>201<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2023, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congressional_=
Caucus_for_the_Equal_Rights_Amendment" title=3D"Congressional Caucus for th=
e Equal Rights Amendment">Congressional Caucus for the Equal Rights Amendme=
nt</a> was founded by House Democrats.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-203" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cit=
e_note-203"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>202<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proposed_removal_of_ratific=
ation_deadline">Proposed removal of ratification deadline</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Proposed removal of=
 ratification deadline"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On March 8, 2011, the 100th anniversary of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/International_Women%27s_Day" title=3D"International Women's Day=
">International Women's Day</a>, Representative <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Tammy_Baldwin" title=3D"Tammy Baldwin">Tammy Baldwin</a> (D-W=
isconsin) introduced legislation (H.J. Res. 47) to remove the congressional=
ly imposed deadline for ratification of the Equal Rights Amendment.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-204" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-204"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>203<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The resolution had 5=
6 cosponsors. The resolution was referred to the Subcommittee on the Consti=
tution by the House Committee on the Judiciary. The Subcommittee failed to =
vote on the resolution, and as such, the resolution died in subcommittee wh=
en the 112th Congress ended in January 2013.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-205" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-205"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>204<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On March 22, 2012, the 40th anniversary of =
the ERA's congressional approval, Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Benjamin_L._Cardin" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Benjamin L. Card=
in">Benjamin L. Cardin</a> (D-Maryland) introduced (S.J. Res. 39)=E2=80=94w=
hich is worded with slight differences from Representative Baldwin's (H.J. =
Res. 47). Senator Cardin was joined by seventeen other senators who cospons=
ored the Senate Joint Resolution. The resolution was referred to Senate Com=
mittee on the Judiciary, where a vote on it was never brought. The resoluti=
on, therefore, died in committee when the 112th Congress ended in January 2=
013.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-206" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-206"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>205<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On February 24, 2013, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
ew_Mexico_House_of_Representatives" title=3D"New Mexico House of Representa=
tives">New Mexico House of Representatives</a> adopted House Memorial No. 7=
 asking that the congressionally imposed deadline for ERA ratification be r=
emoved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-207" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-207"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>206<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-208" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-208"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>207<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> House Memorial No. 7=
 was officially received by the U.S. Senate on January 6, 2014, was designa=
ted as "POM-175" and was referred to the Senate's Committee on the Judiciar=
y.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-209" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-209"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>208<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On January 30, 2019, Representative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Jackie_Speier" title=3D"Jackie Speier">Jackie Speier</a> (D-Califo=
rnia) introduced legislation (<a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" h=
ref=3D"https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-joint-resolution/=
38">H.J.Res.&nbsp;38</a>) in a renewed attempt to remove the deadline to ra=
tify the amendment. As of April 30, 2019, the resolution had 188 co-sponsor=
s, including Republicans <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Reed_=
(politician)" title=3D"Tom Reed (politician)">Tom Reed</a> of New York and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Fitzpatrick_(American_politi=
cian)" title=3D"Brian Fitzpatrick (American politician)">Brian Fitzpatrick<=
/a> of Pennsylvania. It was referred to the Subcommittee on the Constitutio=
n, Civil Rights, and Civil Liberties by the House Committee on the Judiciar=
y on the same day.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-210" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-210"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>209<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The subcommittee heard testimony on the amendment and extension of the=
 deadline on April 30, 2019.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-211" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-211=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>210<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>On November 8, 2019, Representative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Jackie_Speier" title=3D"Jackie Speier">Jackie Speier</a> (D-Califo=
rnia) re-introduced the bill as <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text"=
 href=3D"https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-joint-resolutio=
n/79">H.J.Res.&nbsp;79</a> to attempt to remove the deadline to ratify the =
amendment with 214 co-sponsors (later 224).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-212" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendm=
ent#cite_note-212"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>211<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The House passed H.J. Res. 79 on February 1=
3, 2020, by a vote of 232=E2=80=93183, which was mostly along party lines t=
hough five Republicans joined in support.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-213" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#=
cite_note-213"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>212<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The bill expired without Senate action.
</p><p>At the beginning of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/117=
th_United_States_Congress" title=3D"117th United States Congress">117th Con=
gress</a>, a joint resolution (H.J.Res. 17) to remove the deadline for rati=
fication was again introduced in both chambers, with bipartisan support.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-214" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-214"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>213<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The House passed=
 the resolution by a 222=E2=80=93204 vote on March 17, 2021.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-215" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equa=
l_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-215"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>214<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-216" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amend=
ment#cite_note-216"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>215<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The companion bill, S.J.Res. 1, introduced=
 by Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Cardin" title=3D"B=
en Cardin">Ben Cardin</a>, was co-sponsored by all 50 members of the Senate=
 Democratic Caucus and Republicans <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Lisa_Murkowski" title=3D"Lisa Murkowski">Lisa Murkowski</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Susan_Collins_(politician)" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Susan Collins (politician)">Susan Collins</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-217" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equ=
al_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-217"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>216=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The measure failed as the S=
enate took no action on it.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Minnesota_legislature_resol=
ution">Minnesota legislature resolution</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Minnesota legislature resolution"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On May 19, 2023, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minnesota_=
Legislature" title=3D"Minnesota Legislature">Minnesota Legislature</a> adop=
ted a resolution memorializing Congress to declare the ERA fully ratified b=
y the states, and now the 28th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution. Governor=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Walz" title=3D"Tim Walz">Tim =
Walz</a> signed the legislation on May 26, and it was then sent to Congress=
 and to President <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden" title=
=3D"Joe Biden">Joe Biden</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-218" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-21=
8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>217<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Biden_declaration">Biden de=
claration</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEq=
ual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Biden declaration"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On January 17, 2025, three days before leaving office, President Biden d=
eclared that, in his opinion, the Equal Rights Amendment was the law of the=
 land, stating: "It is long past time to recognize the will of the American=
 people. In keeping with my oath and duty to Constitution and country, I af=
firm what I believe and what three-fourths of the states have ratified: the=
 28th Amendment is the law of the land, guaranteeing all Americans equal ri=
ghts and protections under the law regardless of their sex."<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Kurtzleben_219-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-Kurtzleben-219"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>218<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
declaration has no formal effect, however,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stokols_220-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights=
_Amendment#cite_note-Stokols-220"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>219<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-221" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amend=
ment#cite_note-221"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>220<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the National Archives has said they do=
 not intend to certify the amendment as part of the Constitution, citing "e=
stablished legal, judicial, and procedural decisions" supporting the integr=
ity of the original ratification deadline in the absence of any subsequent =
extension or deadline removal by Congress or the court system.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-222" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eq=
ual_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-222"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Biden's statement led to w=
idespread criticism,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-223" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-223"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>222<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-224" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-224"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>223<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-225" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-225"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>224<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> with the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Washington_Post" title=3D"The Washington =
Post"><i>Washington Post</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.=
1em;">'</span>s</a> analysis concluding "it's also remarkable that a presid=
ent would try to declare something that isn't clearly the law to be not jus=
t the law, but part of the most significant legal document our country has.=
 That at the very least skips over a whole lot of very valid legal issues t=
hat have never been settled."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-226" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-22=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>225<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"State_equal_rights_amendmen=
ts">State equal rights amendments</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DEqual_Rights_Amendment&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: State equal rights amendments"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/State_equal_r=
ights_amendments" title=3D"State equal rights amendments">State equal right=
s amendments</a></div>
<p>Twenty-five states have adopted constitutions or constitutional amendmen=
ts providing that equal rights under the law shall not be denied because of=
 sex. Most of these provisions mirror the broad language of the ERA, while =
the wording in others resembles the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Equal_Protection_Clause" title=3D"Equal Protection Clause">Equal Protecti=
on Clause</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourteenth_Am=
endment_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title=3D"Fourteenth Amendment to=
 the United States Constitution">Fourteenth Amendment</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-CRSReport_100-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-CRSReport-100"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The 1879=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_California" title=
=3D"Constitution of California">Constitution of California</a> contains the=
 earliest state equal rights provision on record. Narrowly written, it limi=
ts the equal rights conferred to "entering or pursuing a business, professi=
on, vocation, or employment". Near the end of the 19th century two more sta=
tes, Wyoming (1890) and Utah (1896), included equal rights provisions in th=
eir constitutions. These provisions were broadly written to ensure politica=
l and civil equality between women and men. Several states crafted and adop=
ted their own equal rights amendments during the 1970s and 1980s, while the=
 ERA was before the states, or afterward.
</p><p>Some equal rights amendments and original constitutional equal right=
s provisions are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CRSReport_100-2" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-CR=
SReport-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-227" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-227"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>226<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-228" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_Rights_Amendment#cite_note-228"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>227<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><b>Alaska</b>: No person is to be denied the enjoyment of any civil=
 or political right because of race, color, creed, sex or national origin. =
The legislature shall implement this section. <i>Alaska Constitution, Artic=
le I, =C2=A7&nbsp;3 (1972)</i></li>
<li><b>California</b>: A person may not be disqualified from entering or pu=
rsuing a business, profession, vocation, or employment because of sex, race=
, creed, color, or national or ethnic origin. <i>California Constitution, A=
rticle I, =C2=A7&nbsp;8 (1879)</i></li>
<li><b>Colorado</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be denied o=
r abridged by the state of Colorado or any of its political subdivisions be=
cause of sex. <i>Colorado Constitution, Article II, =C2=A7&nbsp;29 (1973)</=
i></li>
<li><b>Connecticut</b>: No person shall be denied the equal protection of t=
he law nor be subjected to segregation or discrimination in the exercise or=
 enjoyment of his or her civil or political rights because of religion, rac=
e, color, ancestry, national origin, sex or physical or mental disability. =
<i>Connecticut Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;20 (1984)</i></li>
<li><b>Delaware</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be denied o=
r abridged on account of sex. <i>Delaware Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&n=
bsp;21 (2019)</i></li>
<li><b>Florida</b>: All natural persons, female and male alike, are equal b=
efore the law and have inalienable rights, among which are the right to enj=
oy and defend life and liberty, to pursue happiness, to be rewarded for ind=
ustry, and to acquire, possess and protect property; except that the owners=
hip, inheritance, disposition and possession of real property by aliens ine=
ligible for citizenship may be regulated or prohibited by law. No person sh=
all be deprived of any right because of race, religion, national origin, or=
 physical disability. <i>Florida Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;2 (19=
98)</i></li>
<li><b>Hawaii</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be denied or =
abridged by the State on account of sex. The legislature shall have the pow=
er to enforce, by appropriate legislation, the provisions of this section. =
<i>Hawaii Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;3 (1972)</i></li>
<li><b>Illinois</b>: The equal protection of the laws shall not be denied o=
r abridged on account of sex by the State or its units of local government =
and school districts. <i>Illinois Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;18 (=
1970)</i></li>
<li><b>Indiana</b>: The General Assembly shall not grant to any citizen, or=
 class of citizens, privileges or immunities, which, upon the same terms, s=
hall not equally belong to all citizens. <i>Indiana Constitution, Article I=
, =C2=A7&nbsp;23 (1851)</i></li>
<li><b>Iowa</b>: All men and women are, by nature, free and equal and have =
certain inalienable rights=E2=80=94among which are those of enjoying and de=
fending life and liberty, acquiring, possessing and protecting property, an=
d pursuing and obtaining safety and happiness. <i>Iowa Constitution, Articl=
e I, =C2=A7&nbsp;1 (1998)</i></li>
<li><b>Maryland</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be abridged=
 or denied because of sex. <i>Maryland Constitution, Declaration of Rights,=
 Article 46 (1972)</i></li>
<li><b>Massachusetts</b>: All people are born free and equal, and have cert=
ain natural, essential, and unalienable rights; among which may be reckoned=
 the right of enjoying and defending their lives and liberties; that of acq=
uiring, possessing and protecting property; in fine, that of seeking and ob=
taining their safety and happiness. Equality under the law shall not be den=
ied or abridged because of sex, race, color, creed or national origin. <i>M=
assachusetts Constitution, Part 1, Article 1 as amended by Article CVI by v=
ote of the People, (1976)</i></li>
<li><b>Montana</b>: Individual dignity. The dignity of the human being is i=
nviolable. No person shall be denied the equal protection of the laws. Neit=
her the state nor any person, firm, corporation, or institution shall discr=
iminate against any person in the exercise of his civil or political rights=
 on account of race, color, sex, culture, social origin or condition, or po=
litical or religious ideas. <i>Montana Constitution, Article II, =C2=A7&nbs=
p;4 (1973)</i></li>
<li><b>New Hampshire</b>: All men have certain natural, essential, and inhe=
rent rights among which are, the enjoying and defending life and liberty; a=
cquiring, possessing, and protecting, property; and, in a word, of seeking =
and obtaining happiness. Equality of rights under the law shall not be deni=
ed or abridged by this state on account of race, creed, color, sex or natio=
nal origin. <i>New Hampshire Constitution, Part 1, Article 2 (1974)</i></li=
>
<li><b>New Mexico</b>: No person shall be deprived of life, liberty or prop=
erty without due process of law. Equality of rights under the law shall not=
 be denied on account of the sex of any person. <i>New Mexico Constitution,=
 Article II, =C2=A7&nbsp;18 (1973)</i></li>
<li><b>New York</b>: No person shall be denied the equal protection of the =
laws of this state or any subdivision thereof. No person shall, because of =
race, color, ethnicity, national origin, age, disability, creed [or], relig=
ion, or sex, including sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expressi=
on, pregnancy, pregnancy outcomes, and reproductive healthcare and autonomy=
, be subjected to any discrimination in [his or her] their civil rights by =
any other person or by any firm, corporation, or institution, or by the sta=
te or any agency or subdivision of the state, pursuant to law. <i>New York =
State Constitution, Article 1, Section 11 (2025)</i></li>
<li><b>Oregon</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be denied or =
abridged by the state of Oregon or by any political subdivision in this sta=
te on account of sex. <i>Oregon Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;46 (20=
14)</i></li>
<li><b>Pennsylvania</b>: Equality of rights under the law shall not be deni=
ed or abridged in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania because of the sex of th=
e individual. <i>Pennsylvania Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;28 (1971=
)</i></li>
<li><b>Texas</b>: Equality under the law shall not be denied or abridged be=
cause of sex, race, color, creed, or national origin. This amendment is sel=
f-operative. <i>Texas Constitution, Article I, =C2=A7&nbsp;3a (1972)</i></l=
i>
<li><b>Utah</b>: The rights of citizens of the State of Utah to vote and ho=
ld office shall not be denied or abridged on account of sex. Both male and =
female citizens of this State shall enjoy all civil, political and religiou=
s rights and privileges. <i>Utah Constitution, Article IV, =C2=A7&nbsp;1 (1=
896)</i></li>
<li><b>Virginia</b>: That no person shall be deprived of his life, liberty,=
 or property without due process of law; that the General Assembly shall no=
t pass any law impairing the obligation of contracts; and that the right to=
 be free from any governmental discrimination upon the basis of religious c=
onviction, race, color, sex, or national origin shall not be abridged, exce=
pt that the mere separation of the sexes shall not be considered discrimina=
tion.<i>Va. Const. art. I, =C2=A7&nbsp;11</i></li>
<li><b>Washington</b>: Equality of rights and responsibility under the law =
shall not be denied or abridged on account of sex. <i>Washington Constituti=
on, Article XXXI, =C2=A7&nbsp;1 (1972)</i></li>
<li><b>Wyoming</b>: In their inherent right to life, liberty and the pursui=
t of happiness, all members of the human race are equal. Since equality in =
the enjoyment of natural and civil rights is only made sure through politic=
al equality, the laws of this state affecting the political rights and priv=
ileges of its citizens shall be without distinction of race, color, sex, or=
 any circumstance or condition whatsoever other than the individual incompe=
tency or unworthiness duly ascertained by a court of competent jurisdiction=
. The rights of citizens of the state of Wyoming to vote and hold office sh=
all not be denied or abridged on account of sex. Both male and female citiz=
ens of this state shall equally enjoy all civil, political and religious ri=
ghts and privileges. <i>Wyoming Constitution, Articles I and VI (1890)</i><=
/li></ul>
